edu.iris.dmc.fdsn.station.model

Class Polynomial

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.iris.dmc.fdsn.station.model.BaseFilter
      • edu.iris.dmc.fdsn.station.model.Polynomial
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Filter

    public class Polynomial
extends BaseFilter
    Response: expressed as a polynomial (allows non-linear sensors to be described). Corresponds to SEED blockette 62. Can be used to describe a stage of acquisition or a complete system.

    Java class for PolynomialType complex type.

    The following schema fragment specifies the expected content contained within this class. 

     <complexType name="PolynomialType">
   <complexContent>
     <extension base="{http://www.fdsn.org/xml/station/1}BaseFilterType">
       <sequence>
         <element name="ApproximationType">
           <simpleType>
             <restriction base="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}string">
               <enumeration value="MACLAURIN"/>
             </restriction>
           </simpleType>
         </element>
         <element name="FrequencyLowerBound" type="{http://www.fdsn.org/xml/station/1}FrequencyType"/>
         <element name="FrequencyUpperBound" type="{http://www.fdsn.org/xml/station/1}FrequencyType"/>
         <element name="ApproximationLowerBound" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}decimal"/>
         <element name="ApproximationUpperBound" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}decimal"/>
         <element name="MaximumError" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}decimal"/>
         <element name="Coefficient" maxOccurs="unbounded">
           <complexType>
             <simpleContent>
               <extension base="<http://www.fdsn.org/xml/station/1>FloatNoUnitType">

             </simpleContent>

      • getCoefficient

        public List<Coefficient> getCoefficient()
        Gets the value of the coefficient property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the coefficient property.

        For example, to add a new item, do as follows: 

            getCoefficient().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list Polynomial.Coefficient
